**Category:** essay-draft Aquinas faith-knowledge Kierkegaard vetula practical-wisdom

**Abstract:**
A major essay dated November 14, 1992 (reworked February 2, 1999), on Aquinas's distinction between scitum and creditum. The document argues that Aquinas worked with two incompatible notions of faith - one explicit (assent to revealed truths) and one latent (practical Christian wisdom). Using the figure of the vetula (simple faithful woman), it demonstrates that living faith differs radically from theological knowledge, and that Aquinas's stated position is fundamentally inconsistent.

**AI Recommendation:** Central theoretical essay for the project; develops the vetula argument as key to understanding practical faith.

